An **init system** is the first program, other than the kernel, to be run after a Linux distribution is booted.

init systems
- sysvinit
- OpenRC
- systemd
- SMF
- launchd
- Epoch
- finit
- runit
- s6 + s6-rc
- 66 + 66-rc
- BSD rc.d
- dinit

Features of init systems
- run as PID 1
- adopts orphans
- Main dependencies
- Init script/service format
- Per-service configuration
- Cross-service dependencies/events
- Parallel service startup
- Keeping daemons alive
- Preferred service file supplier
- Filesystem mounting
- getty (terminal prompts)
- Networking setup
- X11 Display Manager setup
- process supervision
- socket activation
- notify about new hardware
- dynamically respond to system events
- targets of systemd comparable to SysVinit RunLevels
- vast number of targets
- Services as Units


